{"id":"1607.03576","submitter":"Dongsheng Zhao","authors":"Dongsheng Zhao and Luoshan Xu","title":"Faithfulness of Directed Complete Posets based on Scott Closed Set\n  Lattices","comments":"8 pages, Domains XII Workshop","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GN","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  By Thron, a topological space $X$ has the property that $C(X)$ isomorphic to\n$C(Y)$ implies $X$ is homeomorphic to $Y$ iff $X$ is sober and $T_D$, where\n$C(X)$ and $C(Y)$ denote the lattices of closed sets of $X$ and $T_0$ space\n$Y$, respectively. When we consider dcpos (directed complete posets) equipped\ntheir Scott topologies, a similar question arises: which dcpos $P$ have the\nproperty that for any dcpo $Q$, $C_\\sigma(P)$ isomorphic to $C_\\sigma(Q)$\nimplies $P$ is isomorphic to $Q$ (such a dcpo $P$ will be called Scott closed\nset lattice faithful, or SCL-faithful in short)? Here $C_{\\sigma}(P)$ and\n$C_{\\sigma}(Q)$ denote the lattices of Scott closed sets of $P$ and $Q$,\nrespectively. Following a characterization of continuous (quasicontinuous)\ndcpos in terms of $C_{\\sigma}(P)$, one easily deduces that every continuous\n(quasicontinuous) dcpo is SCL-faithful. Note that the Scott space of every\ncontinuous (quasicontinuous) dcpo is sober. Compared with Thron's result, one\nnaturally asks whether every SCL-faithful dcpo is sober (with the Scott\ntopology). In this paper we shall prove that some classes of dcpos are\nSCL-faithful, these classes contain some dcpos whose Scott topologies are not\nbounded sober. These results will help to obtain a complete characterization of\nSCL-faithful dcpos in the future.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2016 02:45:45 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-07-14"}
