{"id":"1607.03637","submitter":"Dominic Horsman","authors":"Dominic Horsman, Chris Heunen, Matthew F. Pusey, Jonathan Barrett, and\n  Robert W. Spekkens","title":"Can a quantum state over time resemble a quantum state at a single time?","comments":"18 pages, 3 figures. Published version","journal-ref":"Proc. R. Soc. A 473 (2205), p. 20170395 (2017)","doi":"10.1098/rspa.2017.0395","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Standard quantum theory represents a composite system at a given time by a\njoint state, but it does not prescribe a joint state for a composite of systems\nat different times. If a more even-handed treatment of space and time is\npossible, then such a joint state should be definable, and one might expect it\nto satisfy the following five conditions: that it is a Hermitian operator on\nthe tensor product of the single-time Hilbert spaces; that it represents\nprobabilistic mixing appropriately; that it has the appropriate classical\nlimit; that it has the appropriate single-time marginals; that composing over\nmultiple time-steps is associative. We show that no construction satisfies all\nthese requirements. If an even-handed treatment of space and time is possible,\ntherefore, one or more axioms must be dropped. In particular, if Hermiticity is\ndropped, then we show that the construction is fixed uniquely up to an ordering\nconvention.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2016 08:16:49 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 1 Sep 2017 12:51:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-27"}
